@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

 --- Introduction ----------------------------------------------------

MaxBlue  is a Door program for MAXsBBS version 1.52+.  It creates mail
packets according to the "Blue Wave" format.  This allows the users to
read messages and even reply to them while not logged on to the BBS.

MaxBlue supports:

  * Offline configuration
  * File attaches
  * Netmail messages
  * Local File requesting
  * Sysop bulletins

@endnode

@node "System Requirements" "System Requirements"

 --- System Requirements ---------------------------------------------

To  use  MaxBlue  you  need  at  least Kickstart 2.0 and a lot of ram.
While  scanning  your messagebase MaxBlue allocates 10 bytes for every
message.  So if your message base contains 20000 messages MaxBlue will
allocate  a 200kbytes buffer.  A small base will not only require less
memory,  the  scanning  process  will be completed considerably faster
too.

You also need these libraries:

   - reqtools.library  version 38+
   - EAGUI.library     version 1.1+	(included in the archive)

I  recommend  you  don't  use MaxBlue on a multi node BBS.  Although I
tried  to  avoid  lockups and other problems that might occur on these
systems, nothing has been tested.  Be careful.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

 --- Installation ----------------------------------------------------

Installing MaxBlue is not all that easy, but if you take your time and
follow  the documentation you should be able to install it without any
trouble.

First  create  a  directory called MaxBlue in your Doors directory and
copy  all  the  files  into  this  directory.  Then make the following
assignment:

  Assign MaxBlue:  BBS:Doors/MaxBlue

Add this assignment to your "User-Startup" file as well.

Now  run  the  'SetupDoor' program (found in the MaxBlue:C/ directory)
and enter the following:

  'System'    - The name of your BBS
  'Sysop'     - Your own name
  'Packet'    - A 1 to 8 character string that identifies your BBS

Note that these three strings can NOT be changed after you register!

  'Reg number' - Your 8 digit registration number or 00000000
  'Archiver'   - Four archiver mash and unmash commands
		 Defaults:    Mash               UnMash
		   1) LhA     C:LhA a @F @I      C:LhA x @F @I
		   2) Zip     C:Zip -jrk @F @I   C:UnZip @F -d @I
		   3) LZx     C:LZx a @F @I      C:LZx x @F @I
		   4) Lh0     C:LhA -z a @F @I   C:LhA x @F @I
  'Max freq'   - The maximum number of files users can request
  'Log bits'   - Defines which actions are logged in the logfile
  'Pvt access' - Specifies the access level to all private messages
  'Logfile'    - The logfile, leave empty to disable logging
  'Nodelist'   - Your nodelist directory (empty if you have none)
  'Netmail'    - Areatag and Title for the pseudo netmail area

Save the settings and set up a door function to start MaxBlue from one
of your BBS menus.

Now  for  the  difficult  part...  You have to set the 'echo flag' and
create a pseudo areatag for all local sections

Go to the sections "Sections configure" window and...

    Name:    Lo:  Hi:   Rp:  Max: Frm:To:Del:Lk1:Lk2:Lk3:Als:Fil:Ech:

10: General  5    10000  0       .    .   .  .   .   .   .   .   X   V
11: Software 5    10000  0       .    .   .  .   .   .   .   .   X   V
.
.                      ...set the echo flag for all local sections   ^
.


Then  go  to the "FidoNet mail distribution" window and enter a pseudo
echotag  for  all  local  sections.   Make  sure  that  the tags don't
conflict with other echo tags.


   Sect:  Area:  Dest adrs:  Passwd:  Opt adrs:  Opt Origin: LZH: Old:

..: 10   L_GENERAL   0/0                   0/0                 X    X
..: 11   L_SOFTWARE  0/0                   0/0                 X    X
.
.            ^        ^ Leave this 0/0
.            | Pseudo area tag (use CAPITALS)
.

If you have any real echo areas, just leave them as they are.
   

Now go to the "FidoNet configure" window and enter the following:

  ' * Origin'   - The default origin for echomail messages
  'BBS address' - Your primary BBS address. 0/0 if you have none.

  Set the 'No care impt' flag to allow importing of messages addressed
  to non-existing users.


Now  go  to  the System configure setup window and set the 'Execute on
loggoff' command to:

  "Execute MaxBlue:S/Logoff"

If  you  have  any  other programs you want to execute on logoff enter
them in the above file.


If  you  are  planning  to  use MaxBlue yourself locally then edit the
files "MaxBlue:S/LocalUpload" and "MaxBlue:S/LocalUpload"


If  you  are connected to one or more mail networks then edit the file
"MaxBlue:MaxBlue.netinfo"  For each network you have to enter your own
address  followed  by  the net/node of your host.  These addresses are
used to determine to which node netmail messages should be exported.

MaxBlue assumes you use these default paths:

          User file file path:    BBS:Userfiles/
      Message files file path:    BBS:Messages/
     Attached files file path:    BBS:AttachedFiles/
              Files file path:    BBS:Files/

      InBound files file path:    BBS:FidoNet/InBound/
    OutBound directories path:    BBS:FidoNet/OutBound/


Well, that's all...  ;-)

@endnode

@node "MaxBlue Files" "MaxBlue Files"

 --- MaxBlue Files ---------------------------------------------------

  MaxBlue		- The executable.  Do  not  run  as  a  normal
			  AmigaDos program, it will probably crash due
			  to a bug in the startup code (not my code).
  MaxBlue.doorinfo	- Configuration file for MaxBlue.   This  file
			  is created by the SetupDoor program.
  MaxBlue.netinfo	- Example netmail info file
  MaxBlue.userdata	- Information of MaxBlue users
  MaxBlue.userindex	- Index file for userdata file
  Text/HelpBundle	- Help page with bundeling commands
  Text/HelpConfig	- Help page for configuration menu
  Text/HelpMain		- Help page for main menu
  Text/Intro		- Introduction page for MaxBlue
  Text/MenuConfig	- Configuration menu
  Text/MenuMain		- Main menu
  Text/NewUser		- Page shown to first time users
  Text/Reader		- File  containing  sysop  bulletins,  read it
			  for more information.
  C/CheckInbound	- Checks for packets in import directory
  C/EditUsers		- Program to view user settings
  C/ResetNetmailBit	- Resets the netmail bit of imported pvt msgs
  C/SelectMenu		- Selects a function from the menu bar!
  C/SetupDoor		- Setup general info about MaxBlue/BBS
  C/UpdateUser		- Updates bbs user settings
  S/Import		- Script to auto import messages after logoff
  S/LocalDownload	- Local download script, sysop use only
  S/LocalUpload		- Local upload script, sysop use only
  S/Logoff		- Script to execute after logoff

@endnode

@node "Shareware" "Shareware"

 --- Shareware -------------------------------------------------------

MaxBlue  is provided to you as shareware.  This means that you can try
the  program for free, but if you want to continue using MaxBlue after
the trial period you should register your copy.

The  unregistered  version  of MaxBlue is fully functional but has one
limitation.   Users are allowed to upload only two messages at a time.
If upload packets contain more than two messages, MaxBlue will display
a  warning  and skip the rest of the packet.

When  you  register  you  will  receive an 8-digit registration number
which  you  must enter in the "Reg number" field.  A valid number will
remove the two message limit.

IMPORTANT:   When you register specify the system name, sysop name and
packet id exactly as you have defined them with the SetupDoor program.
Once  you  have  received  your registration number you can not change
them so choose carefully.

See  the @{" registration.form " link "registration.form/main" } file  for  more  information  on  how
to register.

@endnode

@node "Additional notes" "Additional notes"

 --- Additional notes ------------------------------------------------

MaxBlue  users  have  the  ability  to  attach files to their uploaded
messages.   To  accomplish this they must copy the file to be attached
to  the  work  directory of their offline reader and enter the name of
the  file  in  the  subject  field  of the message header preceeded by
'ATT:'

@endnode
